We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the Municipal Engineer to ensure that the abovementioned provisions under Republic Act 11058 and its Implementing Rules and Regulation and DOLE Department Order No. 198 are faithfully complied with;
Require the Municipal Engineer to consistently remind the winning contractor of the strict compliance for the use of Personal Protective Equipment, Safety Signage, and Devices wherein the cost of these were consistently charged as line item under Construction Safety and Health Program which forms part in the projects’ Program of Works.  This measure is also essential to prevent unforeseen injuries or damages that may cause tremendous pecuniary liabilities;
Require the Municipal Engineer to regularly monitor the attendance of the First Aider and the Safety Officer, whose salaries were included as part of the projects’ cost; and
Require the Municipal Engineer to reflect in the SWA, the absence of these components, which means reduction in the amount to be finally paid to the contractor. If already paid, require the contractor to refund the cost of these items.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer for timely submission of all financial transaction documents and other related reports;
Create an effective system of communicating the release of checks to recipients and ensure their timely release as well as the submission of the financial transaction documents and other reports.

We have recommended the Management to:
Absolutely prohibit disbursements that are, under the law, not defined as for public purpose/s;
Completely desist from granting financial endowments to LEAD or association;
Require from LEAD a copy of its latest financial and accounting records and a detailed report on how the P1,000,000.00 grant was utilized;
Exercise due diligence and keen prudence in filling out pertinent details of documents to be submitted to the focal/accountable officers and/or the Audit Team.

We have recommended that Management:
Effectively strategize or carefully plan every project before funds of the LGU are used;
Require the MPDC and the Municipal Engineering Office to draft a proposal as to how the idle property be functionally used.

In view of the foregoing deficiencies, we have recommended the following –

The LGU should exert diligent efforts to locate the necessary documents supporting their claims in order to establish the legitimacy of the receivable accounts;

When a receivable account is confirmed to be non-moving or remained to be inactive in the books of accounts for ten (10) years or more and where settlements or collectability could no longer be ascertained, it shall be considered a dormant receivable account. In this regard, management should be guided by procedures on the write-off of dormant receivable accounts under COA Circular 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We have recommended the following:

Limit the procurement of goods and services on a reimbursement basis, unless the circumstances warrant its application;

Require the Municipal Treasurer to adhere strictly to the provision that all payments should be made by check directly payable to the suppliers;

Require the Municipal Accountant to deduct the corresponding withholding taxes in all disbursements required by the BIR; and

Adopt public bidding or alternative modes of procurement provided under RA No. 9184 to promote transparency and to avoid possible source of irregularities.

We have recommended that Management –

Strictly comply with the documentary requirements provided under COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 and ensure the completeness of supporting documents before affixing signatures in the disbursement vouchers and before effecting payments pursuant to Section 4(6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445;

Attach the missing supporting documents such as Travel order and certificate of appearance for the subject transactions;

Require the issuance of Property Acknowledgment Receipt for the release of equipment to end-users to determine accountability. Also, PAR should be attached to disbursement vouchers before payments are effected; and

Ensure that the necessary forms or documents should be completely or appropriately accomplished.

For the foregoing deficiencies noted, we have recommended that –

The Municipal Health Officer verify and submit certification that the procured drugs and medicines still on stocks in the Rural Health Units fall within and conform to the latest edition of the PNDF Manual;

The concerned Municipal Health officials see to it that in the subsequent purchases, the purchase request be supported with the certification as required by the regulation;

In case the medicines are not included in the PNDF Manual, prepare a written request with justification and secure approval from the Director, National Center for Pharmaceutical Access and Management;

Strict compliance with the documentary requirements for procurement of drugs and medicines provided under Section 9.1.3.1 of COA Circular 2012-001 is further recommended.

We reiterated our audit recommendation that Management strictly comply with the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Roads Asset Management System prescribed in COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015. We further recommended the following courses of action:
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network, and disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the total road network system;
Require the Municipal Treasurer, in the absence of General Services Officer, to maintain a Report of the Local Road Network and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;
Conduct physical count and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System.

Management commented that the Local Government Unit of Laoac through the Office of the Municipal Engineer together with the Inventory Committee conducted Physical Count to identify roads to be repaired and to be concreted and be included in the Local Road Network Development Plan, however, they were informed through AOM that the prepared Local Road Network Inventory Report was not in prescribed format. With that, Management expressed its willingness to comply with the audit recommendations and correct the following deficiencies.

We recommended that Management undertake the following actions in the disposal of unserviceable/obsolete property and equipment, to wit:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer, in the absence of General Services Officer, to report all unserviceable property and equipment of the LGU in the Inventory and Inspection Report for Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) and ensure that the said report be duly accomplished;
Create a Disposal/Appraisal Committee to administer and manage the disposal process;
Ensure that the unserviceable/obsolete property and equipment be disposed pursuant to Section 379 of RA No. 7160 and COA Circular No. 89-296 dated January 27, 1989.  Likewise, be guided accordingly with the guidelines set forth under Chapter 7 of the Training Handbook on Property & Supply Management System in the appraisal and disposal of properties;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the unserviceable/obsolete property and equipment to Other Assets account while awaiting its final disposal to ensure fairness of presentation of PPE accounts in the interim financial reports.

Management commented that a Municipal Disposal and Appraisal Committee has been created. Management also agreed to comply with the given audit recommendations.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and the BAC Secretariat to post all NOA, contract, or purchase order in the website of the local government unit, if any, or any conspicuous place in the premises of the PE and GPPB online portal for Emergency Procurement under the Bayanihan Act for information purposes and to require the submission of the mandatory documentary requirements from the concerned suppliers;
Require the MSWDO to secure documents certifying that the nearest relative of the deceased PUI is not financially capable of defraying the expenses for the burial such as certificate of indigency to support the claims;
Require the Municipal Accountant and MSWDO to submit the list of affected families and proof of receipt of distribution of relief goods and other supporting documents, and to submit comments/justifications on the deficiencies noted.

Management commented that working on a state of paranoia during enhanced community quarantine period brought by the COVID-19 pandemic was a big challenge for everyone and the urgent delivery of required services to their constituents was their top priority and their awareness on some technical procedures had been on the side.

Nonetheless, Management would like to correct the noted deficiencies by submitting the required documents. However, they regret that they could no longer post the Notices of Award on the GPPB Online Portal but they have posted it at conspicuous places in the Municipality.

