The LGU Management apologized for the deficiencies made on said payments. For the subsequent periods, Management expressed its intention to strictly adhere to the provisions stated on COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 48 of RA No. 9184. Management also assured the Audit Team on the compliance with the recommended courses of actions.

We have recommended that the Municipal Accountant –

Review the transactions charged to Construction in Progress accounts and ensure that only accumulated cost of land improvements, infrastructure assets, buildings or structures which are still in the process of construction, development or acquisition be recorded thereof;

Make proper reclassification to the appropriate PPE accounts upon completion; 

Reconcile with the records of the Office of the Municipal Engineer and disclose the details of Construction in Progress accounts in the notes to financial statements and subsidiary schedule;

Make necessary adjusting or correcting entries and strictly observe the proper accounts prescribed in the Revised Chart of Accounts for Local Government Units for accurate and reliable presentation of the affected accounts in the financial statements.

In view of the foregoing, we have recommended that Management:

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to transfer the PCSO funds received to the General Fund and ensure that appropriations are provided therefor in the utilization thereof;  

To submit copies of Memorandum of Agreement entered into between the LGU with PCSO for CY 2019 indicating the category of programs for which its allocation or funds may be utilized and the reportorial requirements pertaining to its utilization as stated in Section 40 of the 2016 Revised IRR for the Small Town Lottery Operations of the PCSO.

In view of the foregoing deficiencies, we have recommended that Management –

Ensure competitiveness and transparency by observing the procedural guidelines on shopping and small value procurement in the purchase of meals and snacks, if competitive bidding is not applicable or cannot be undertaken;

Attach the missing supporting documents such as Purchase Request, Purchase Order, Acceptance and Inspection Report, BAC Resolution, Request for Quotation from at least 3 suppliers, and Cash/Charge Sales Invoice with corresponding Collection Receipt (if applicable) for the subject transactions to avoid the issuance of Notice of Suspension;

Prepare and submit Activity Design/Training Program to indicate details of the activity undertaken. Similarly, minutes of meetings, agendas/programs and list of recipients/attendance should also be attached as an addition to establish reasonableness of the claims;

Ensure the completeness of supporting documents before affixing signatures in the disbursement vouchers and before effecting payments pursuant to Section 4(6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445; and 

Strictly observe the proper accounts prescribed in the Revised Chart of Accounts for Local Government Units for accurate and reliable presentation of the affected accounts in the financial statements.

We have recommended that Management strictly comply with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the granting and liquidation of cash advances. It is further recommended that:

The Municipal Administration stop the practice of granting cash advances to officials and employees who are not designated disbursing officers and for purposes other than those allowed under Section 3 of COA Circular No. 97-002; 

Require the Municipal Treasurer to make payment thru check directly in the name of the supplier or creditor instead of granting cash advances;

Stop the granting of cash advances to elected officials other than for traveling expenses in compliance with Section 4.1.4 of COA Circular No. 97-002;

No additional Cash Advance shall be given to officials/employees unless the previous cash advance was first settled;

All cash advances shall be supported by an Accountant’s Certification that the requesting party has no existing unliquidated cash advances; and

Withhold the salaries of officials and employees whose cash advance remains unliquidated once efforts yield no encouraging results.

